   <mods:abstract>The Duke of Orleans has asked De Limon to pass the following statements on
            to all curates: that the right of property is inviolable, that it ought not be taken
            even in the public interest; that all taxes should be levied equally on rich and poor;
            that the Duke of Orleans has joined the bailliages; that no obstacle should be placed in
            the way of just and reasonable demands of the third estate, i.e., relative to its
            rights; that De Limon is ready to listen to the complaints of villagers and laborers and
            to protect their rights and credit. If these guidelines are followed, a curate may
            expect to acquire a genuine right to the good favor of the Duke of Orleans. Printed
            Circular Letter (in French).</mods:abstract>
